<DOC><DOCNO> AP880723-0106 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-88 1415EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Monsoon     07-23 0221</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Monsoon,0227</SECOND><HEAD>Monsoon Toll Rises to 255</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rains and landslides were reportedacross India on Saturday, and the death toll from the annualmonsoon rains rose to 255, reports said.   The hill resort of Simla in the northern state of HimachalPradesh was cut off for the third day, the Press Trust of Indiareported. Rail and road traffic to Simla, the state capital, hasbeen disrupted because of landslides and heavy rains.   At least 20 more deaths were reported as a result of the rain,which began last month. The rain, eagerly awaited by Indians afterthree years of drought, has caused widespread flooding.   In New Delhi, officials began evacuating people living inlow-lying areas near the Yamuna river.   Warnings were issued to villagers living on the outskirts of thecapital because of the rising water levels of the river, the PressTrust of India said.   Five people died in Himachal Pradesh state in floods orlandslides, the United News of India reported.   Eight more people were killed when heavy rains caused a mudslidein northeastern Bombay, the news agency said.   Three people died in Jammu district in Kashmir state when theirhut collapsed, and four people died in Uttar Pradesh state, UNIsaid. Most of the deaths occurred in the past 24 hours.</TEXT></DOC>